Here are both approaches for Shell navigation in .NET MAUI:

**1. Register the route:**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — string parameter vs. full object:**
```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs
[RelayCommand]
async Task OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    // Approach A: pass just the ID as a string
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?id={product.Id}");

    // Approach B: pass the full object via dictionary
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        ["product"] = product
    });
}
```

**3. Receive data with `IQueryAttributable`:**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsViewModel.cs
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private Product _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: string parameter — comes in as a string
        if (query.TryGetValue("id", out var idObj) && idObj is string id)
        {
            // fetch product from service using the ID
            Product = _productService.GetById(id);
        }

        // Approach B: full object — arrives as the original type
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            Product = product;
        }
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String (`?key=val`) | Object (dictionary) |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | URI query string | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Value type** | Always `string` | Original CLR type preserved |
| **Use case** | Deep links, simple IDs | Complex objects, non-serializable data |
| **Deep-link safe** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |

> **Tip:** Wire the VM to the page via DI (`builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsPage, ProductDetailsViewModel>()`) so `ApplyQueryAttributes` is called automatically on the page's `BindingContext`.
